    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Home Theater</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Michael Paschkes letter, commenting on May 31 article, suggests that Broadway producers send videos of their plays to members of the Tony Award nominating committee and Tony voters to ensure that they see all the shows</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Special Twists This Year in the Competition Called Tony Madness'' (Arts pages, May 31):</p>
        <p>You report that it is frustrating and costly for Broadway producers as they try to insure that the nominating committee and voters for the Tony Awards see their shows.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Special Twists This Year in the Competition Called Tony Madness'' (Arts pages, May 31):</p>
        <p>You report that it is frustrating and costly for Broadway producers as they try to insure that the nominating committee and voters for the Tony Awards see their shows.</p>
        <p>Since the shows have all probably been videotaped for various purposes, why not just send tapes to the committee and voters? Not only would this save the cost of all of the free tickets, but it would also save the time and cost of the viewers getting to theaters on specific days and at specific hours.</p>
        <p>They might miss the ambience and audience reaction, but that should not factor into judging a show.</p>
        <p>MICHAEL PASCHKES  Bronx, June 1, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
